ICMP data visualisation

Bevan Weir

data as of 21 October 2021

Introduction

This is an R Markdown document for statistics derived from specimen data of the ICMP culture collection https://www.landcareresearch.co.nz/icmp. This is an experimental showcase of presenting visulisations of data analysed in R in a user-friendly format.

General statistics

The ICMP database has 22946 entries, removing cultures that have died and are no longer available (‘deaccessioned’) there are 22227 cultures. This total includes cultures stored privately not available to the public, and those in the process of storage. The total number of publicly available cultures is 19504. Most of the stats below use the ‘total minus deaccessioned’ number as the base data.

(also should include NZ only stats)

Type cultures

The ICMP has a number of type cultures.

ICMP.types <- subset(ICMP.dump,!(TypeStatus == ""))
table(ICMP.types$SpecimenType)
## 
## Bacterial Culture  Chromist Culture    Fungal Culture     Yeast Culture 
##               580                13               346                 4

There are different ‘kinds’ of types. Bacterial types are ‘type strains’, bacterial pathovars are ‘pathotype strains’. Fungal type cultures may have been isolated from a type specimen (e.g. from PDD) and are thus ‘ex types’.

Extended specimen data

Extended specimen data is data beyond the basic taxonomic and and location. See: https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/70/1/23/5637849 The charts below show the proportion of ICMP cultures that have DNA sequences lodged in GenBank global repository, images (usually of culture plates), and when a culture is specifically cited in literature.

This data can be split by the type of specimen (Bacteria, Fungi, Chromist, Yeast) to show the relative proportions of extended specimen data for each of these.

Host plants

Many ICMP cultures are associated with a host plant, for example rhizobia in legume nodules, or plant pathogenic fungi causing leaf spots. Below are the top 10 most common host plant families in the ICMP with type of organism.

There are various ways to divide Aotearoa New Zealand in regions. The ICMP uses ‘Crosby Codes’ which were developed for for recording specimen localities in the New Zealand. The ICMP is based in Auckland explaining the large number of collections from this region.

Isolation month

In the New Zealand autumn, May is the peak mushroom fruiting season explain the number of fungi isolated in this month. In general there is a trend of fewer isolations in Winter and more in Summer. The high numbers in January may be an artifact of a prior way recording the data in the database which if the month was unknown it would be recorded as January.

less in winter, more in summer trend.
